25:48.670 --> 25:53.878
The New Testament is a polemic book almost from beginning to end.

25:54.419 --> 26:06.418
Some years ago, I was in a company of teachers, which says of the Bible in colleges and other educational institutions of America, one of the most eminent theological professors in the country made an address.

26:06.690 --> 26:22.371
In it, he admitted that there were unfortunate controversies about doctrines in the epistles of Paul, but said he, in effect, the real essence of Paul's teaching is found in the hymn to Christian love in the thirteenth chapter of the first Corinthians.

26:23.012 --> 26:29.260
And we can avoid controversy today if we will only devote the chief attention to that inspiring hymn.

26:30.702 --> 26:36.530
In reply, I am bound to say, that the example was

26:37.474 --> 26:40.678
singularly ill-chosen.

26:40.698 --> 26:48.146
That hymn to Christian love is in the midst of a great polemic passage.

26:48.166 --> 26:56.435
It would never have been written if Paul had been opposed to controversy with error in the church.

26:57.316 --> 27:05.906
It was because his soul was stirred within him by a wrong use of spiritual gifts that he was able to write that glorious hymn.

27:06.434 --> 27:08.036
So it is always in the church.

27:08.637 --> 27:16.208
Every really great Christian utterance, it may almost be said, is born in controversy.

27:16.989 --> 27:29.187
